{
  "doc_id": "9403",
  "text": "Research is increasingly aimed at identifying genetic determinants of stress vulnerability as risk factors for mental disorders. It has been proposed that dysregulation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, a key system in the biological stress response, is a component of vulnerability for psychiatric disorders [CITATION_1] . Genetic factors account for approximately 50% of variability in cortisol secretion [CITATION_2] , a measure of HPA activity. Thus, it appears that some genes, in concert with other genetic and environmental factors [CITATION_3] , determine individual differences in HPA activity. Dopamine has also been implicated in the stress response [CITATION_4] , and one of the genes responsible for dopamine metabolism, Catechol-O-Methyltransferase (COMT) is among the genes theorized to impact stress-sensitivity [CITATION_5] . COMT Val 108/158 Met is a functional polymorphism (i.e., a single nucleotide involving an amino acid change from Valine (Val) to Methionine (Met) at codon 158) affecting enzyme activity. Val homozygosity is associated with 3-4 fold higher enzyme activity than Met homozygosity [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , and because the alleles are codominant, heterozygotes are intermediate (Männisto and Kaakkola, 1999; [CITATION_8] . Accordingly, Val/Val, Val/Met and Met/Met genotypes correspond, in theory, to highest, intermediary, and lowest dopamine degradation, respectively. Two mechanisms have been suggested for COMT allelic variants to alter HPA function [CITATION_9] . First, because low-activity COMT (Met variant) is associated with higher catecholinergic activity, it would be expected to be linked with greater hypothalamic corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) release. Second, more pronounced μ-opioid receptor binding potential has been observed in response to stress in humans who are COMT Met/ Met homozygous [CITATION_10] , suggesting that the low-activity form of COMT could alter HPA activity indirectly through influencing DA-mediated regulation of opioid neurotransmission.",
